metadata.name: Konstruktion v0.5 #38
metadata.description:
Further exploration of mathematical beauty and chaos combining to build an elemental konstruktion in space. It started a few weeks ago as a vague concept in my mind, leading to the development of a unique form that transcends normal design.

Every generated piece is so unique that I cannot conceive of a feature or classification system. Please enjoy the beauty of this creation!

Release v0.5 is limited to screen resolution save (using "s" or "S" as described below). If you're interested in high-resolution images, please consider release v1.0.

All proceeds shared with Three.js and Girls Who Code.

Interactive with several user controls:

With the mouse:

Left click and drag to change the viewing angle

With the keyboard:

The "f" key will freeze the animation entirely. This can be used if you want to save the image at a specific viewpoint.

Keys "," and "." (or "<" and ">") change the rotation speed left or right. You can stop it entirely, or speed it up to what I consider a reasonable maximum, rotating to the left or to the right. Each time you press, it adjusts the rotation speed.

Key "s" will save to a ".png" file at screen resolution.
Key "S" will save to a ".jpg" file at screen resolution.

metadata.name: Terra-Bytes #199
metadata.description:
Terra-bytes is a generative art project of landscapes sculpted in virtual reality.

The work is composed of more than 10 different types of landscapes, each divided into 5 layers of depth that are mixed together generating millions of possible combinations.
In addition, these landscapes are accompanied by different characters, objects and elements that give life and complexity to each generated scene, making it unique.
Each visual element of this work was sculpted in VR with virtual hands and then exported to Blender for post processing and rendering.

Many thanks to @Purespider for the template.
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

---- On Tuesday, February 14, unsold editions will be burned ----

metadata.name: Décollage #370
metadata.description:
A generative sketch based on the concept of décollage, an artistic process that involves cutting or tearing pieces of an original image. The resulting outputs bear a resemblance to artworks produced using the lacerated poster technique, where posters are layered and torn to reveal parts of the posters underneath.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels. Note that this will not work with sizes beyond 5000 pixels.

(Allowlist is based on quantity of previous works owned).

metadata.name: INSTRUCTURES #414
metadata.description:
Instructures explores the endless and diverse outcomes when a minimal and straightforward set of instructions are followed to build structures out of cubes. Between 4 and 8 instructions are selected and used to generate a unique structure for each edition. The available instructions are “stack”, “pile”, “plane” and “sculpt”. As a last step, flat and/or rounded corner details are optionally added to each structure.

Each artwork includes the set of instructions that were followed to build the structure. These instructions can be followed to build new structures using other methods in addition to programming, e.g. sculpting, printing, drawing, painting etc., and I plan on using this body of work to do exactly that. This project is, in fact, the result of an algorithm initially developed to generate interesting compositions and structures out of cubes to be used as points of departure for drawings, prints and paintings.

Even though the algorithm is focused on generating unique structures, the additional variations in scale, composition, colour, viewing angle and drawing style create an even wider array of generative outcomes. Some outputs are recognisable as three-dimensional orthographic drawings while others are more abstract. Instructures attempts to strike a balance between traditional art and the more technical nature of computer and blockchain art by blending visual cues from both disciplines. My hope is that the works can be appreciated by audiences from both of these worlds.

“The idea becomes a machine that makes the art.” — Sol Lewitt

Hotkeys
=======
Each artwork is interactive allowing the viewer to rotate, move and zoom in on the structure.

[H]elp — Complete list of available hotkeys
[I]nstructions – Instructions for structure
[F]eatures
[P]rint sizes
[Right click, save] – Save PNG image

[Z]oom
[W] Move up
[S] Move down
[A] Move left
[D] Move right
[<] Rotate clockwise
[>] Rotate anti-clockwise

Original artwork by Herman Pretorius, 2022

metadata.name: Incomlete #31
metadata.description:
Incomplete is normal while complete is unnormal.
Each artwork has one status: Normal, Complete, or Rare.

Even you can pause or rewind the process, you still can't change the incomplete result.
Learn to enjoy the incomplete is the only way. 
Just like your life.

The blocks will move and combine. We could have multiple point of view for the incomplete:
4 different Types according to the distance.
3 level of Stroke for different style.
3 types of Shadow and light.
2 different Materials of blocks.
And 40 selected color Palettes with different amount and angle of blocks

[Interact]
[p] Pause 
[r] Rewind 
[s] Save in PNG 

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Feathery Friend #13
metadata.description:
This is not a generative project, rather a PFP (layered PNGs) of a feathered friend of mine. She lays, she squawks, and she jumps on my shoulder when gestured. I love her, and I hope you love her too!

Thank you @Purespider for making fxhash accessible to new aspiring artists!

metadata.name: Geo Scribs #14
metadata.description: The aesthetic of projector slides and transparent sheets becharmed my younger studious self. The inaccuracies, finger smudges and colorful markers gave texture and humanness to the coldest mathematical diagrams. The imperfectness of our teachers would be exhibited to us all as the potent light would shine through the tentative circles on those wobbly sheets.

metadata.name: Ries #294
metadata.description:
Ries is 500 sheets of paper. 
Ries is an cut-up text-artwork.
Ries is artwork generated by an algorithm based on seeded random numbers.
Ries is a digital artwork installed in 5 forms in exhibitions setting.
Ries is an NFT artwork. 

Ries is an artwork where I try bring together my experience of doing gallery exhibitions, my love for generative and copy machine art, DIY-punk aesthetics, NFT’s and chaos. 

The edition of Ries will be installed in different forms and collages in a gallery exhibition in Walden Kunstaustellungen in Berlin in July of 2022. Opening is at 8.7. 19.00, welcome if you are in Berlin.
/www.galerie-walden.de/

The seed idea for the project was the method of cut-up where a text (or something else) is cut into pieces and then rearranged to form something new. A modified Markov’s Chain algorithm makes a small text or a group of words from a pool of texts that include Art texts about cut up technique and generative art talk from tweets. These words form a visual bottom layer and then another layer of words samples the first, cutting it up and thus following the theme of the artwork.

Since the single iterations of the project are designed to be used in a collage, they come in various tone, density, detail and scale. One can test from the variations button and get a sense of what the generator produces. 

Controls in live view:
-Pressing  j exports the current image as jpeg
-Pressing  p  exports the current image as png

To change the detail level one can access the pixel density of render by adding ?pixDens=4 to the end of the URL in live view. You can of course you any number other than 4 also. I it renders just a black image, you have to lower the number, since it is then too large for WEBGL to render.

Designed to be best rendered on desktop Chrome.

Pricing info
22 tez - Includes a gallery shown, signed print sent to minter by mail or by telefax(!)
11 tez - A fair price for an artwork, also the minter can personally pick up a signed gallery shown print from the gallery, after the exhibition.
5 tez - 1/2 fair price
2 tez - bottom dollar

If you minted on lower tiers and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm to “upgrade”. If you bought secondary, and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm.

Features exist mostly to help with artwork pairing for the collectors.


Markov’s chain code core is based on Markov Me! By https://codepen.io/alexkramerbanjo , MIT License

Displacement shader based on the wonderful shader examples by Adam Ferris


The artist holds the right to use the whole edition of Ries for display purposes for future exhibitions without asking permission or notifying the owners of the NFT’s.

1.7.2022 in Berlin
Antti Pussinen

www.anttipussinen.net
www.twitter.com/antti_pussinen
www.instagram.com/anttipussinen
